		<header>
			
			<h1>Pacific–EU EPA trade talks stalled because of tuna issues</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>After the Pacific Trade delegation’s visit to Brussels to discuss the EPA, the <i>Samoa Observer</i> announced that “the possibility of wrapping up the trade negotiations between the Pacific and the European Union is fading.”</p><p>The Solomon Islands National Trade Negotiations envoy emphasised that: “Fish is the only issue standing in the way of progressing and concluding their EPA with the EU.” The challenges for the EPA are how to treat market access for fish products – especially the global sourcing derogation – and related issues of effective conservation and management measures, such as the Parties to the Nauru Agreement (PNA) Vessel Day Scheme (VDS).</p><p>Regarding global sourcing, it was commented that “the EU wanted some guarantee that the fish will be coming from the region.” This comes as the Spanish processing company ANFACO made allegations that canned tuna processed in the Philippines is being smuggled into Papua New Guinea (PNG) by a Philippine company having a processing facility there, and re-exported into the EU market, illegally using the global sourcing derogation to avoid higher duties. PNG National Fisheries Authority have ordered a full investigation into the allegations, and requested ANFACO to provide evidence of their allegations.</p><p>Another issue for Pacific ACP (PACP) nations and the EU is how to take into account the PNA, in particular the VDS scheme which aims at increasing benefits from the tuna fisheries and improving the management of this resource. The PNA brings together eight Pacific Island countries: Federated States of Micronesia (FSM), Kiribati, Marshall Islands, Nauru, Palau, Papua New Guinea, Solomon Islands and Tuvalu. Together, these countries own waters that supply 25% of the world’s tuna, estimated at US$2 billion every year. But six Pacific ACP countries are not members of the PNA. Doubts have been voiced on the EC side about the transparency and efficiency of the scheme.</p><p>After the meeting between the PACP delegation and high-level EC officials, Samoa’s Ambassador to the EU, chair of the ACP Committee of Ambassadors, stated that ‘a plan B’ had been discussed: “We have now said ‘let’s take a break’ – there is no time frame in terms of another meeting.” But the outcome of the talks is still ambiguous. Speaking to the press, Fiji’s Trade Minister denied reports that EPA negotiations were suspended: issues had been identified, and that they “need to regroup as a region”. The Fijian Trade Minister said, “The Pacific bloc has been given time to solve pending issues before they can continue negotiations.”</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Samoa Observer</i>, ‘EU trade talks stalled’, 20&nbsp;October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://samoaobserver.ws/other/economy/7590-eu-trade-talks-stalled" target="_self">http://samoaobserver.ws/other/economy/7590-eu-trade-talks-stalled</a></p><p><i>Atuna.com</i>, ‘PNG requests ANFACO to render evidence on “smuggling”’, 28&nbsp;October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13577" target="_self">http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13577</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The Cotonou Agreement emphasises that EPAs are to be based on ACP countries’ regional integration initiatives. In the Pacific, fisheries are the main shared resource and, through trade and licensing arrangements, one of the main sources of economic benefits for the whole region. For both trade and licensing arrangements, the PACP–EU EPA negotiations have been quite complicated until now, with difficult discussions regarding the extension of global sourcing or the endorsement of the regional access to the VDS. Now that both parties are “taking a break”, this suggests that a PACP common strategy should be identified so that regional integration efforts are supported by future relations with the EU. However, the EP recently voted in favour of a comprehensive fishery strategy for the Pacific, calling for the necessary coherence of EU trade and fisheries policies with development objectives. This may be a pertinent element for rebuilding a fruitful dialogue.</p>
		</div>
		
